## Context
Editor's personal emphasis (E3/E4) + Reviewer 1 ┬¦2: the historyŌåöquant relation
is thin and the quantitative analysis is transparent but unjustified. Also owns
Reviewer 2's headline point (R2a): the central claim ŌĆö that the categories which
made climate finance measurable also made it politically contestable, because
the translation from qualitative realities into quantitative indicators is
inherently indeterminate ŌĆö is "potentially innovative" but must be substantiated
explicitly throughout, not merely asserted.

## Actions
0. (R2a) Make the indeterminacy thesis the explicit analytic spine: state it plainly early, then substantiate it at each act with concrete evidence that the qualitativeŌåÆquantitative translation was underdetermined and that this underdetermination is what opened political contestation. Pairs with the commensuration/economisation thread (0137).
1. Frame the quant role explicitly up front: confirmatory / exploratory / generative ŌĆö and state which findings are which.
2. Resolve directionality: are the three traditions derived from Table 1 or imposed on it? State it. Mobilise Figure 2 in the ┬¦1 argument (or cut it).
3. Add a methods justification (appendix or expanded methods note) answering: corpus construction (sources/docs/reports + boundary criteria, grey-lit inclusion, institutional-doc exclusion, econ-journal underrepresentation); why three periods + how detected; why co-citation + the 250-doc limit in ┬¦2; Louvain vs Leiden + modularity 0.68; full-text cleaning; k-means + k + robustness checks.
4. Address the burden-sharing divergence (R1.2): ┬¦1.3 anchors Negishi 1960 but co-citation shows North 1990, DiMaggio & Powell 1983, Finnemore & Sikkink 1998 ŌĆö reflect on what this means for the tradition's weight.
5. Cross-link to the technical-report / data-paper where methods are already justified; import the strongest justifications.

